Title: CS15: Gerp

Names: Nick Ferrari and Mason Coleman

Ackowledgements:

Files: 
    Gerp.cpp: This class serves as the main engine for the search program, 
    handling the indexing of file directories and responding to user queries. 
    It manages the FSTree navigation, dual-table hashing for case sensitivity, 
    and efficient line-based data retrieval.

    Gerp.h: This class coordinates the indexing and searching of a directory 
    system. It manages the file system traversal, populates dual hash tables 
    for case-sensitive and insensitive searching, and executes the main command 
    loop for user queries.

    HashTable.cpp: This class provides near-constant time search functionality 
    for a string search engine. It handles collisions via separate chaining and
    maintains performance by dynamically doubling its capacity when the load 
    factor reaches 0.75.

    HashTable.h: Defines the structure for the word index used in the gerp 
    search engine. This class supports efficient storage and retrieval of line
    numbers associated with unique words, adhering to strict memory 
    constraints.

    main.cpp: This file handles command-line argument validation and 
    initializes the Gerp engine to begin the indexing and query process.

    unit_tests.h: Tests for the functions in processing.cpp

Compile/run: To compile the program, run make from the project directory. This 
will produce an executable called gerp. To run the program, use the command 
./gerp inputDirectory outputFile, where inputDirectory is the directory you 
want to search and outputFile is the file where results will be written. 
Once the program is running, it accepts prompt: any word performs a 
case-sensitive search. @i or @insensitive followed by a word performs a 
case-insensitive search. @f followed by a filename redirects all further 
output to that new file; and @q or @quit exits the program.

Architectural overview: The program is organized around a Gerp object, which is
created in main.cpp and drives the entire cycle of the search engine by calling 
run() with the input directory and output filename. The Gerp class coordinates 
three phases: indexing, querying, and output. During indexing, Gerp constructs 
an FSTree from the directory. FSTree holds a pointer to the root DirNode, and 
each DirNode holds a vector of filenames and a vector of pointers to its child 
DirNodes. buildFilePaths performs a recursive pre-order traversal of this tree,
collecting every file path into a vector. Each file is then processed, which 
reads every line, stores it as a struct, and inserts each word into two 
HashTable instances: sensitiveTable and insensitiveTable. During querying,
commandLoop reads commands. Depending on the command, lookups go into either 
sensitiveTable or insensitiveTable. Those indices are used to get the original 
line text and file path, which are then written to the output file.

Data Sturctures/Algorithms used: The core data structure is a hash table 
implemented in HashTable.cpp. Each bucket in the table holds a linked list of 
HashNode structs, where each node stores a word as the key and a vector of 
integers as the value. Each integer in that vector is an index into the vector, 
pointing to a line where that word appears. We chose a hash table because both 
insertion and lookup are O(1). The table starts with a capacity of 1000 and 
doubles in size whenever the load factor exceeds 0.75, at which point all 
existing nodes are rehashed into the new table.
We maintain two separate hash tables: sensitiveTable stores words exactly as 
they appear, while insensitiveTable stores every word converted to lowercase. 
This means both case-sensitive and case-insensitive queries can be answered. 
Duplicate word occurrences on the same line are suppressed in HashTable::insert 
by checking whether the incoming line index equals lineNumbers.back() before 
appending. Since words on a line are processed left to right, duplicate words 
on the same line produce consecutive identical indices, and this check prevents 
the same line from appearing twice in query results.

Testing: Testing was carried out in two phases. For the functions in 
processing.cpp, we wrote unit tests in unit_tests.cpp. The stripNonAlphaNum 
function was tested with strings that needed no stripping, strings with 
leading-only or trailing-only non-alphanumeric characters, strings with 
non-alphanumeric characters on both ends, strings where interior characters 
must be preserved, strings composed entirely of non-alphanumeric characters 
which should return an empty string, and empty string input. For diff testing, 
we used the test directories provided at /comp/15/files/proj-gerp-test-dirs. 
We began with tinyData, a small directory designed for quick iteration, which 
let us verify basic correctness of indexing and querying before moving to 
larger inputs. We then ran the program against the small, medium, and large 
Gutenberg subsets. These were run directly from the course directory without 
copying them locally, for example by passing 
/comp/15/files/proj-gerp-test-dirs/mediumGutenberg as the directory argument. 
For each test, we ran both our implementation and reference implementation on 
the same set of queries, captured both output files, and diffed them against 
each other. Queries covered both case-sensitive and case-insensitive searches. 
The medium and large Gutenberg directories also served as stress tests for 
time and space efficiency.

